    {
      "source": "hackernews",
      "subsource": "news.ycombinator.com",
      "category": "ai",
      "title": "Did Claude increase bugs in rsync?",
      "url": "https://alexispurslane.github.io/rsync-analysis/",
      "discuss_url": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48411635",
      "score": 141,
      "comments": 142,
      "author": "logicprog",
      "published": "2026-06-05T12:43:33Z",
      "bullets": [
        "AI-generated PRs from Claude and ChatGPT for legacy C tools like rsync frequently introduce hallucinated flags and subtle logic bugs.",
        "LLMs struggle with complex codebase-specific contexts, generating syntactically correct but functionally broken code that bypasses basic static analysis.",
        "The influx of low-quality AI code increases maintainer fatigue, highlighting the need for stricter automated CI/CD gating in open-source repositories."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/programming",
      "category": "engineering",
      "title": "Win16 Memory Management",
      "url": "http://www.os2museum.com/wp/win16-memory-management/",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/c3xmxm",
      "score": 5,
      "comments": 0,
      "author": "calvin",
      "published": "2026-06-05T17:31:03Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Win16 used x86 16-bit segmented memory addressing (16:16), mapping selectors to physical descriptors to bypass the 64KB limit.",
        "Developers managed memory via `GlobalAlloc` and `LocalAlloc`, requiring explicit handle locking (`GlobalLock`) to prevent fragmentation via relocatable blocks.",
        "Windows 3.x navigated Intel 8086 Real Mode, 286 Standard Mode (16MB limit), and 386 Enhanced Mode with hardware-enforced virtual memory."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/security",
      "category": "security",
      "title": "The Empty Field That Wasn't: GPS Broadcasts a Numbers Station",
      "url": "https://lsc-pagepro.mydigitalpublication.com/publication/?i=865273&p=62&view=issueViewer",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/a7v7e5",
      "score": 14,
      "comments": 3,
      "author": "lordgilman",
      "published": "2026-06-05T13:07:50Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Analysis of GPS LNAV (L1 C/A) navigation messages reveals that reserved bits defined as static in IS-GPS-200 contain active data.",
        "This undocumented payload acts as an orbital covert channel, transmitting changing, pseudorandom sequences directly from US Space Force satellites.",
        "Security analysts and receiver developers must update parsers to handle arbitrary data in reserved fields to prevent decoding anomalies."
      ]
    },
